        "content": "<p>The following code example is in the Mechanics of Proof course.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"n\">termination_by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I wanted to understand what <code>termination_by</code> does but can't find any online explanation after searching using the mains search engines. From the brief explanation in MoP and the hover tooltip I assume it is:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>a recursive function is <strong>required</strong> to terminate (is this correct, or is this only required if we arbitrarily evaluate such a function rather than reason using its constructors)</li>\n<li>Lean is <strong>told</strong> what measure decreases (without proof?)  as the evaluation approaches termination, here it is <code>a+b</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Question 1:</strong> Is this correct?</p>\n<p><strong>Question 2:</strong> Why does the same code cause an error in a vanilla Lean environment? The error is as follows:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Text only\"><pre><span></span><code>3 parameters bound in `termination_by`, but the body of pascal only binds 2 parameters.\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 497794148,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1738721300
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"724904\">rzeta0</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/termination-by.20-.20MoP.20vs.20vanilla.20lean/near/497794148\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>a recursive function is <strong>required</strong> to terminate (is this correct, or is this only required if we arbitrarily evaluate such a function rather than reason using its constructors)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Lean is <strong>told</strong> what measure decreases (without proof?)  as the evaluation approaches termination, here it is <code>a+b</code><br>\n</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>My understanding is that every function not marked <code>partial</code> or <code>unsafe</code>, or <code>partial_fixpoint</code> has to terminate on all possible combinations of inputs, because you can extract a contradiction from a non-terminating function.</p>\n<p>Here, Lean is told what measure to use, and then it attempts to automatically generate a proof that the measure is decreasing. In this case it succeeds.</p>",
        "id": 497795763,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1738722293
    },
    {
        "content": "<hr>\n<p>I've experimented and edited the code to make it appear to work: I have no idea if it is correct:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"n\">termination_by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span>\n\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">pascal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p><strong>Question 3</strong>: Also why is the <code>termination_by</code> using an <code>=&gt;</code> ? What is this symbol?</p>",
        "id": 497795813,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1738722329
